  "prompt": "Why did the government of India introduced a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note?",
  "response": "The decision by the Indian government to introduce a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note in 2016 was part of a broader strategy during the demonetization process. There are several reasons why the 2000 rupee note was introduced:\n\n1. **Remonetization Strategy**: The introduction of the 2000 rupee note was part of the remonetization process following the sudden demonetization of the 500 and 1000 rupee notes. The aim was to quickly replenish the currency supply in the economy with higher denomination notes, which would be easier to distribute and manage in large volumes.\n\n2. **Convenience and Efficiency**: Higher denomination notes allow for larger transactions with fewer notes, improving the efficiency of cash handling, storage, and transportation. Introducing a 2000 rupee note meant that larger sums of money could be transacted more conveniently than with the older 1000 rupee notes.\n\n3. **Curbing Black Money**: By introducing a higher denomination, the government sought to address issues related to black money. The initial demonetization sought to eliminate unaccounted cash hoarded by individuals. The introduction of a 2000 rupee note was supposed to be more traceable and was accompanied by measures to promote cashless transactions, thereby increasing financial transparency.\n\n4. **Technological and Security Features**: The new 2000 rupee notes included advanced security features aimed at curbing counterfeiting, a significant problem with the old 500 and 1000 rupee notes.\n\n5. **Symbolic Move**: The introduction of the 2000 rupee note can also be interpreted as a symbolic move, signifying a fresh start post-demonetization, with new designs and features aligning with the government's developmental and economic reform goals.\n\nOverall, the introduction of the 2000 rupee note was a strategic decision within the context of India\u2019s economic policies at the time, aiming to address various monetary and fiscal challenges following demonetization.",
